<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Much that we'll need to know concerns the information stored in computers, which is why we find ourselves using psychological words like 'knows', 'thinks', and 'wants' in referring to machines, even though machines are very different from humans and these words arose from the human need to talk about other humans.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>We may say of an automatic teller machine, 'It thinks I don't have enough money in my account because it doesn't yet know about the deposit I made this morning.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Few of us know much about how the electric light system or the telephone system work internally.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>we know that lights are turned on and off by switches and how to dial telephone numbers.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>For more than a century we have used machines in our daily lives whose detailed functioning most of us don't understand.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>We do know their external behavior;</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>We may not know much about the internal combustion engine, but we know that a car needs more gas when the gauge reads near EMPTY.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>In the next century we'll be increasingly faced with much more complex computer based systems.</a>
